<div id="review_2538716640" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2538716640" />
    <a title="Jack Vasen" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/52966326-jack-vasen"><img alt="Jack Vasen" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1456179595p2/52966326.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2538716640?book_show_action=true">Sep 22, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jack Vasen" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jack Vasen" href="/user/show/52966326-jack-vasen">Jack Vasen</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/52966326-jack-vasen?shelf=christian">christian</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/52966326-jack-vasen?shelf=adventure">adventure</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/52966326-jack-vasen?shelf=mature-themes">mature-themes</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/52966326-jack-vasen?shelf=fantasy">fantasy</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2538716640" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17669652006425238603">This is the second of the series which is a long continuing saga of the legend of King Arthur. It ends at a convenient stopping point, but I didn&apos;t think that the story stood by itself.<br/><br/>The first section titled King, is off to a decent start. The material is different from approaches to the legend that I&apos;m familiar with. Section 2, Forest Lord, is where this book starts to fall apart. For starters, since the entire book is first person narration by Merlin, most of this section is intended to conv</span>
  <span id="freeText17669652006425238603" style="display:none">This is the second of the series which is a long continuing saga of the legend of King Arthur. It ends at a convenient stopping point, but I didn't think that the story stood by itself.<br /><br />The first section titled King, is off to a decent start. The material is different from approaches to the legend that I'm familiar with. Section 2, Forest Lord, is where this book starts to fall apart. For starters, since the entire book is first person narration by Merlin, most of this section is intended to convey that Merlin is now a raving lunatic. It rambles and is difficult to follow. But then, to make matters worse, about half way through, there are a few pages that vividly describe horrors I really wish I could have done without. After that, the rest of the book follows the part of the legend that most of us know well and for me became tedious at times since I knew what was coming.<br /><br />I might have added the Romance shelf, but chose not to. almost but not quite arbitrarily. What there was of romance consisted of another mindless love at first sight. From the third section on, the book proceeds. with one brief exception, almost as if that part of it didn't happen.<br /><br />Lawhead continues to mix Christianity with Druid practices.<br /><br />Mature themes: there are several gory battle scenes. But most disturbing is a scene of off-the-chart-brutal murders of innocents which includes sexual mutilation. Given that in most, if not all, of Lawhead's works he goes out of his way to avoid description of sex even between married people, I don't see why he needs to include vivid descriptions of violence that are to the point of being offensive to a reader who is at all sensitive. In books of this and related genres, I expect war violence and death and maybe even references to pillaging against civilians (such as occurred in Book 1 while war raged on Atlantis), but I would really prefer that the description did not go to this extreme.<br /><br />I really didn't even want to give this 2 stars.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17669652006425238603" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


