<div id="review_3504785027" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3504785027" />
    <a title="Cynthia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/64108855-cynthia"><img alt="Cynthia" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1498592275p2/64108855.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3504785027?book_show_action=true">Dec 08, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Cynthia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Cynthia" href="/user/show/64108855-cynthia">Cynthia</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/6591782-merlin">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3504785027" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6024845052134625020">If it wasn&apos;t for Merlin stating at the start of the book that this story isn&apos;t about him but of how Arthur came to be, I would have been a tad bit disappointed in the book. Merlin did pave way for Arthur and because of him Arthur exists and this book is basically about that. Of course for that to happen we have to see Merlin grow up and go through life in all it&apos;s unfairness. <br/>Okay so, did I like the book, yes but not as much as I liked Taelisin. It&apos;s Merlin I expected something different than wh</span>
  <span id="freeText6024845052134625020" style="display:none">If it wasn't for Merlin stating at the start of the book that this story isn't about him but of how Arthur came to be, I would have been a tad bit disappointed in the book. Merlin did pave way for Arthur and because of him Arthur exists and this book is basically about that. Of course for that to happen we have to see Merlin grow up and go through life in all it's unfairness. <br />Okay so, did I like the book, yes but not as much as I liked Taelisin. It's Merlin I expected something different than what I got. That being said Stephens' writing kept me hooked until the very end. The only thing that I have wasn't sure about was the Christianity aspect of the book. Initially when it was introduced in book 1 I thought it would go in a different direction but we are in book two and Christianity has almost completely overshadowed the old ways. I thought Merlin would be the bridge between the two but that was a disappointment. I don't have a problem with the way it was presented because it felt natural except for one chapter. After Arthur was born and Merlin was going through "temptations", the whole Charis casting out evil spirits and mentioning Satan felt forced. That whole chapter threw me off and I get what Stephen was trying to do but it felt more like the Author was inserting himself into the story. Maybe it's just me but it just didn't feel natural. <br />Now the important question, will I continue with the series? I wasn't sure at first but I've thought about it and yes I will. Merlin didn't go through all that for me to not see whether his efforts paid off or not. And I did not sit through Merlin paving way for Arthur just so that I wouldn't read about it. Also there's Morgian, I want to know about her plans.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6024845052134625020" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


